    <list type="translations">
        <item xml:lang="zh">平坦的</item>
        <item xml:lang="och">平／夷</item>
    </list>
<div type="definition">
<p>SURFACE which is the SAME in HEIGHT EVERYWHERE.</p>
    </div>
<div type="notes">
<div type="old-chinese-criteria">
<p>1. The general word for flatness of any kind is píng 平 (ant. qīng 傾 "slanted downwards on one side" and perhaps xié 斜 "sloping") and it refers to anything which is horizontal and lacks inclination.</p>
<p>2. Yí 夷 (ant. xiǎn 險 "precarious or difficult of access (of terrain)" and yì 易 mostly refers to terrain and its accessibility through lack of geographical impediments.</p>
<p>3. Tǎn 坦 (dǒu 陡 "steep") has no special pragmatic connotations and simply refers to the objective property of a an area without noticeable elevations.</p>
        </div>
